Episode 22 | Teaching your next date how to cook.   Serves 2: One cutie pie and one stallion. Difficulty: Slam dunk; you got this!  User guide notes: 1. Super easy to make. You can skip the whole pasta-making process or peeled tomatoes.  2. One garlic is enough; don't play with fire.  3. Place your plates in the oven at 100Â°C/212Â°F. Helps keep your food warm as your plate! 4. Go for a dry white wine; i.e.; Riesling or Pinot Grigio.   Pasta Sauce (for 2): - 1 garlic clove - 1-2 small chillies - 250g cherry tomatoes* - Splash of white wine - 150g finely diced prawns - 150g fish or chicken stock - Good splash of olive oil  *For peeled skin; score an "x" at the core of the tomato skin and blanch for 10 secs in boiling water; place under call water or ice bath!  Steps to success:  Heat a frying pan until hot; add olive oil and prawns. Cook until they have a nice colour on one side remove immediately and place in a container (you don't want to overcook). Allow the same pan to cool; then add a bit more olive oil and finely diced garlic clove and small chilli(s). Gently heat until fragrant but do not burn (be careful it goes quickly with garlic and chillies). Add cherry tomatoes and stir through until slightly broken and soft. Add a splash of white wine and reduce. Add stock and reduce by 3/4. Set aside and keep warm.   Assembly: - Small handful of parsley finely chopped - 40g parmesan cheese (30g approx for sauce and remainder 10g for garnish) - Salt and Pepper to taste  Steps for success:  Once your pasta is cooked to al dente add directly into the sauce. Add finely chopped parsley and parmesan cheese and stir through. Divide portions between two plates. Garnish with a bit of parsley and parmesan cheese.   Semolina Pasta (for 2): - 125g Semolina Flour  - 1 egg + 1 egg yolk - 1 teaspoon olive oil  - Pinch of sea salt  Process: Combine everything and kneed into a smooth dough. Wrap up and allow to rest for 30 min in the fridge before proceeding to make the pasta sheets. The suggestion here is to go on the lower-end setting so you have thin pasta sheets. You can cut them into strips if you don't have additional pasta attachments. Dust with plenty of flour and cook until al dente.

A Flaky Start: Exhibit B - Croissant & Hot Chocolate. #croissants  #hotchocolate  #pastries  #desserts   Taste 8/10 Visuals 7/10  Hot chocolate recipe (serves 2-4) - 200g chopped dark chocolate - 2 tablespoon of brown sugar - 2 tablespoons of cacao powder - pinch of sea salt - 400g organic milk

I want to be that freaky fantasy that is always on your mind. #desserts  #praline  #parisbrest  #pastries   Taste 8/10  Visuals 5/10  Here we have a classic Paris Brest with Praline Moussaline. I served it with a coffee and tonka ice cream; chocolate sauce; and easy whipped cream. Ingredients and notes below!  Filling - 240g heavy cream  - 150g milk  - 1x vanilla pod - 80g caster sugar - 60g egg yolks - 40g corn starch - 125g white chocolate (to be added into the hot custard) - 250g praline - 150g butter  Choux (makes to large rings): - 125g milk  - 125g water - 125g butter - 6g salt - 8g sugar - 380g flour - 250g eggs (5x approx.)

Episode 21 | Teaching your next date how to cook. #datenight  #ramennoodles  #ramenhacks  #saucy   5-star Fast Food Ramen Recipe! Taste 9/10 Difficulty: Easy to Medium   Briefing: So here we have an easy-peasy date night recipe dish. Super fun and it tastes delicious. Tbh; I think this is one of my favourites amongst the churros and dessert pizza.  Before you begin: Serves 2; so you need 2 noodle packets. I went with Korean noodles for this recipe but you could switch it up as you please. So; if you went for more Japanese ramen noodle packets then switch the Gochujang with miso paste for example.   Garnish Ideas:  - Pork Belly (recipe below) - House-made ramen (check serious eats) - Seaweed - Mozzarella shreds  - Rice cakes  - Soft-boiled egg - Scallions  Ramen Broth for 2 Part 1 - 2 packets of Korean instant ramen broth powder + 600g water - A few slices of spring onions; 4 button mushrooms finely slices; a few slices of fresh ginger; and 4 dried shitake mushrooms (optional) - 16 gelatine bloomed sheets for a silkier mouth feel (optional)  Process: Add together and allow to simmer for 30 minutes. Strain and add bloomed gelatine. Mix until well combined and keep warm. Heat before serving.   Part 2 (per bowl) -	1 egg yolk -	1 tsp Gochujang -	2 tsp kewpie mayo  -	1 tsp sweet soy sauce  -	1 tsp regular soy sauce -	1 tsp olive oil  -	1 tsp sesame oil  Process: Add everything in a bowl and mix. Repeat the process with the second bowl. When all your other garnishes are ready and prepped; add gently half of your hot broth and mix in.   Pork Belly Recipe - 400g pork belly - 1kg  water + 1 chicken stock cube - 330g light soy sauce - 225g sweet soy sauce  - 81g packed brown sugar - 125g oyster sauce - 9 star anise  - 5 black peppercorns - 15 ginger slices  - 2 garlic cloves - 2 cinnamon sticks  - 1 bay leave  - 30g Gochujang (optional)  Process: Add everything to a medium to a large pot. Bring to boil with the pork belly then back to a gentle simmer for 1.5 to 2hrs. Allow to cool slightly then slice to desired thickness. Notes: Use 300g of leftover stock and reduce until it thickens. Use this stock to baste pork belly slices and torch to get a beautiful char/caramelization.

Arancini with Arrabbiata sauce made using @Napolina â€™s finest chopped tomatoes #AD  #NotSoHumbleIngredients   Recipe   Arrabbiata Sauce:   1 onion 5 cloves garlic  1/2 tsp chilli flakes  1 tbsp Napolina tomato puree  2 tins Napolina chopped tomaotoes  6 basil leaves   Arancini:   1 onion  2 cups Arborio rice  4 cups chicken (or vegetable) stock  25g butter  1/2 cup parmesan  1 mozzarella ball  2 eggs  breadcrumbs  oil for frying   For the Arrabbiata sauce; begin with finely chopping the onion (plus an extra one for the Arancini) and garlic.  Get a pan on a medium heat and add two tbsp of olive oil. Add the chilli flakes and cook for 1-2 minutes. Add the onions and sweat down for a further 2-3 minutes. Add the garlic; stir and then squeeze in the tomato paste. Stir well.  Add the tin tomatoes; with a little water and the basil leaves. Give it one final stir and leave to simmer on low for 30 minutes.  For the Arancini; add two tbsp of olive oil to a sauce pan on medium - high heat and add the onions. Sweat down for a couple of minutes and then add the rice. Mix well and cook for 1 minute. Then add the stock. Cover and leave to simmer following package instructions (roughly 10-12 minutes).  Once the rice is cooked add the butter and parmesan; stir through and remove from the heat.  Spread the rice out over a baking tray and leave to fully cool.  Slice the Mozzarella into cubes.  Using wet hands grab a small handful of the rice. Place the mozzarella in the middle and roll into golf ball size balls.  Ideally you should let them set in the fridge for at least two hours (but if you can't wait then march on).  Crack two eggs into a bowl and whisk well.  Add the breadcrumbs (season to your preference) to a plate.  Drop the Arancini into the eggs and then straight into the bread crumbs. Make sure they are evenly coated and shake off the excess.  In a deep sauce pan heat 2 1/2 inches of oil (canola; sunflower etc) and heat to 180c/350f.  Carefully drop the Arancini into the oil. Move them every so often so they don't stick to the bottom and burn.  Once a deep golden brown colour; remove and place onto paper towel. Season with a little salt.  Let them rest for a couple of minutes and then serve with the Arrabbiata sauce on the side.  Enjoy!
